The anniversary of the 2025 Pahalgam attack marks a definitive turning point in India’s national security doctrine. It was the moment that moved the India from a decades-long policy of "Strategic Restraint" to a posture of "Proactive Deterrence."  

By launching Operation Sindoor and suspending the Indus Waters Treaty, India signaled that terror is no longer a non-state actor issue but an state sponsered act of war. Pakistan's "nuclear bluff" has been called, and the new normal is one of set, cost-imposing retaliation. India’s core has shifted: from seeking global empathy to enforcing accountability on those who back terrorism.

